	></iframe></div><p style=";text-align:right;direction:rtl"> Based on ratios of publications that include local authors and those that don&#39;t, the team developed an index for countries most at risk for parachute paleontology. Those countries include places like the Dominican Republic, Myanmar and Namibia, the team reported in the same study <em>.</em> But the problem is widespread, they found.</p><div class="wp-block-sciencenews-content-sidebar alignwide" style=";text-align:right;direction:rtl"><h3 class="wp-block-heading" style=";text-align:right;direction:rtl"> At risk</h3><p style=";text-align:right;direction:rtl"> To measure how parachute paleontology impacts countries, paleobiologist Nussaïbah Raja and colleagues created an index number, based on the ratio of the number of domestic to foreign authors on papers about fossils from those countries. The Dominican Republic and Myanmar, which top the list, are both hot spots for fossils preserved in amber, which have become highly commercialized. </p><iframe
